There are still some limitations in the present study. Although the fundamental domain of the original surface obtained by our method can be embedded in \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathbb{E}}^{2}$$\end{document}, it cannot be tessellated. That is, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathbb{E}}^{2}$$\end{document} could not be covered by the fundamental domain of the original surface under any transformation group. Therefore, we must develop periodic boundary conditions, which are frequently used in computational fluid dynamics, to make textures smooth and continuous near the cut graph of the original surface.
